        {
            "title": "COPING: How civil servants deal with stress during public service delivery",
            "date": {
                "start": {
                    "month": 8,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2013
                },
                "end": {
                    "month": 8,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2013
                }
            },
            "description": "Funded by the EU's FP7 framework, the COPING project analyses how civil servants cope with stress during public service delivery. For instance, how does a teacher cope with the stress associated with a high workload? Will he give some high achieving children substantial attention, while disregarding the others ('creaming strategy')? Or will he for instance ration all children, giving them all less attention, but equally divided? \n\nThis project is being executed in close collaboration with prof. dr. Victor Bekkers (Erasmus University Rotterdam) and prof. dr. Michael Musheno (UC Berkeley). \n\nThe EU FP7 Marie Curie Grant allows me to become a Visiting Scholar at the University of California, Berkeley, for the full academic year 2013-2014. Here, I will combine psychology and public administration research to develop - with others - a new research line on the 'psychology of public administration'. ",
